description: Edges & point fairly sharp; mid rib extending up to point, and angular in section; a rib extends on each wing, parallel to the edge and curves in near the base to join the loops; both loops are diamond-shaped, one of them being slightly broken.  Orifices of socket partly missing; stump of wooden shaft remains in socket.  There is a crack across the front where the socket meets the blade and the spearhead is slightly bent at this point.  DECORATION, Lines of punched [...] at intervals of about 1mm along each side of apex of mid rib and base of mid rib, on both sides of the blade.  Socket has incised line near its mouth & 8 mm higher up are six more incised lines .  From the last of these six incised lines springs a chevron pattern, which goes round the whole circumference of the socket, the chevrons being fitted with hatched lines.  Compare spearhead III a from BAINBRIDGE N.R. Yorks, for similar ornament.

site: England,Shropshire,Little Wenlock,Willow Moor (alias Wrekin Tenement),1835,1834. Dukes.
toSearch: Little Wenlock, Telford, Telford and Wrekin TF6, UK
associations: Part of a hoard
description: Badly damaged, very thin metal, socket about 1/4mm thick. 2 Rivet holes.,Mr Pritchard writes to L.F. Chitty, 31-10-23: "The 3 broken spearheads (bronze) were found in 1835 during excavations in connection with drainage of Willow Moor Farm. Of course the finder is dead, also his son who kept them in memory of his father; I knew the son casually but cannot find out his name. I have no reason to doubt the authenticity of the specimens. Along with the bronze spearheads was found a stone celt (knife LFC) also in my possession"
publications: As "Wrekin Tenement" 1834. T.F. Dukes. Nov 20, 1834, in Arch XVI. 464-5,Brief mentions in Arch. Camb. III (4th S.) 338., & Montgom. Colln. III, 437.,Evans B. Imps. pp. 285. 338. 461. 465.,As "Willow Moor, Willow Farm, or Wrekin Farm. 1835" Hartshorne, Salopia Antiqua (1841),Arch. Jour. VIII (1851) 197.,Shrops. Arch. Trans. IV (2) 279. "Wrekin Farm", but pp 89-98 & plate, quoting Evans "Wrekin Tenement," as "Near Little Wenlock " cont'd below
remarks: References etc contd from above:,or "Little Wenlock, Stap" (error amended later). Evans B. Imp. (Hoard No 44) pp. 44. 13. 234. 134. 336. 452. 461. 465.,He recognized that this was "possibly the same hoard as No 41" (Wrekin Tenement)",Anden. Vic. Co. Hist. Shrops I. 203.,That these two hoards are identical is proved by the same spearhead with lunated openings & socketed celt with a notch chipped in the edge, occurring in each.

Chitty 31.10.23: "The 3 broken spearheads (bronze) were found in 1835 during excavations in connection with drainage of Willow Moor Farm. Of course the finder is dead, also his son who kept them in memory of his father; I knew the son casually but can not find out his name. I have no reason to doubt the authenticity of the specimens. publications: As. Wrekin Tenement 1834, T.F. Dukes, Nov. 20, 1834, in Arch XXVI, 464-5.,Brief mentions in Arch. Camb. III (4th S), 338, + Montgom. Collection III, 437,As "Willow Morr. Willow Farm, or Wrekin Farm, 1835", Hartshorne, Salopia Antiqua (1841); Arch Jour. VIII (1851) 197.; Shrops. Arch. Trans. IV (2) 279. "Wrekin Farm" but pp. 89-98 + plate quoting Evans "Wrekin Tenement", as "Near Little Wenlock" or "Little Wenlock, Stop" (error amended later). Evans B. Imps (Hoard No. 44) pp. 44, 113, 234, 314, 336, 452, 461, 465. He recognised that this was "possibly the same hoard as No. 41 (Wrekin Tenement)". That these two hoards are identical is proved by the same spearhead with limited openings + socketed celt with a notch chipped in the edge, or curving in each.  Anden, Vic. Co. Hist. Shrops. I, 203.
